A team of diggers has started removing 2,500 tonnes of waste from a 40ft-high rat-infested rubbish pile which has blighted the lives of residents for the past three years.

The towering mountain of putrid rubbish sits at the end of cul-de-sac near Orpington, Kent, and is laden with everything 
imaginable - from rotting industrial waste, old shoes and broken fridges 
to tyres, scrap metal, excrement, discarded nappies and plastic bottles.

The stinking mound - which residents say 'smells like rotting corpses' - is also prone to catching fire, as 'hot spots' smoulder deep inside the 60-ft wide pile of rubbish. Fire crews have now been called to 23 fires at the site - one of which lasted ten days - which has cost the taxpayer £650,000.

